# SQL / PL-SQL Formatting Standards

## 1. Indentation & Case
- Use **2 spaces** for indentation. DO NOT USE TABS.
- **SQL/PLSQL keywords**: ALL lowercase (e.g. `select`, `begin`, `if`).
- **Identifiers**: snake_case (e.g. `l_count`, `tf_tickets`).

## 2. Lists & Commas
- **Leading Commas**: Place commas at the beginning of the line for lists (columns, parameters).
- **Vertical Alignment**: Align identifiers, types, column names, and assignments vertically for readability.
- **Operators**: Place SQL operators (`and`, `or`) at the beginning of the line.

## 3. IF / THEN Formatting
Keep `if` condition and `then` on the **same line**. Do not put `then` on a separate line.

**GOOD**:
```sql
if l_name is not null then
  -- logic
end if;
```

**BAD**:
```sql
if l_name is not null
then
  -- logic
end if;
```

## 4. Code Sectioning
- Level 1 blocks use `=`
- Level 2 blocks use `-`

```sql
-- =============================================================================
-- IMPORTANT SETTINGS
-- =============================================================================

-- -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
-- Minor logic
-- -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
```

## 5. TODOs
Follow this mandatory format:
`-- TODO_[Initials]_<MONTH-DD-YYYY> [Description]`

**GOOD**:
`-- TODO_AFLORES_MARCH-09-2026 Pending review`
